is accent, Broxton decided to get a speech coach in an attempt to “sound like a white person”. Upon completion of the 12-week speech training, Broxton was able to find a job within 3 weeks, but he could barely recognize his own voice. %0a%3c %0a%3c Broxton has been reporting in Montana, surrounded by mostly white people, for 3 years now and says that he had to “completely change who I am” in order to fit in. He now only uses his natural accent when he goes home and is surrounded by other black people. When asked about needing to change his accent Broxton says that there are double-standards with accents. He goes on to question that if Bill Clinton was able to become the President of the United States with a southern accent, why aren’t tv reporters allowed to have an AAVE accent?%0a%3c %0a%3c In conclusion, this article explains Broxton’s struggle with linguistic discrimination and the steps that he had to take in order to overcome accentism and get a reporter job.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
